Case Study 

Cybercrime types - 

Phishing is a type of cybercrime in which attackers attempt to steal sensitive information such as usernames,
passwords, and bank details by pretending to be a trustworthy source. 
  
This is usually done through fake emails, messages, or websites that appear genuine.

In a typical phishing attack, the victim receives an email or message that looks like it is from a bank, online service,
or trusted organization. 
  
The message often creates a sense of urgency, asking the user to click on a link to verify their account or update details. 
When the user clicks the link, they are redirected to a fake website that looks identical to the original. Once the user
 enters their login details or personal information, the attacker captures the data.

Students and individuals who are not aware of such scams are common targets. The consequences can be serious, 
including financial loss, identity theft, and unauthorized access to personal accounts.

Phishing attacks are increasing rapidly due to the widespread use of digital platforms. 
Therefore, it is important to stay alert and verify the authenticity of messages before taking any action online.

